{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"alias":"clay-feast-strife","description":"# Content-addressed snapshot cache + background janitor\n\n## Why\n\nThe same SHA is often requested by multiple concurrent gates; re-materializing identical\ncontent per call is wasteful. An immutable SHA is a perfect cache key (no staleness), so\n`<cache>/<sha>/` is content-addressed. The hard part is RECLAMATION under disk pressure\nwithout corrupting concurrent readers — the spike showed our original PID+heartbeat lease is\nunsound (cannot represent N readers; PID reuse; crash-stale). Use kernel guarantees instead,\nmirroring Gitaly / Sourcegraph gitserver / Bazel / ccache.\n\n## What\n\n- Cache entries keyed by SHA, populated via S1's atomic dir-rename; single-flight per SHA\n  (in-process lock/future + optional cross-process `flock(LOCK_EX)` on `locks/<sha>`).\n- Reader safety via POSIX delete-on-last-close: readers `open()` files up front; evicting an\n  entry under an open fd is harmless; `ENOENT`/`EIO`/short-read -> treat as miss -> re-materialize.\n- LRU recency via mtime TOUCHED-ON-READ (never `atime`; broken under relatime/noatime).\n- Single background janitor in the server (off the hot path): primary trigger = FREE-SPACE\n  watermark (`shutil.disk_usage`), backstopped by an incrementally-maintained byte total\n  (no hot-path `du`); secondary max-age trim for cold entries.\n- Eviction mechanism: `rename(<sha>, trash/<uuid>)` (atomic disappearance from canonical\n  path) THEN `rmtree` the trash entry — never in-place `rmtree` (races readers); skip entries\n  within a short mtime grace window.\n- Cross-process GC interlock: hold an exclusive `flock` on `<cache>/gc/lock` per GC pass\n  (Bazel `gc/lock` pattern); population stays lock-free.\n- Startup sweep: `rmtree tmp/* trash/*`; reconcile byte-total with one full walk.\n- Self-heal: read-error -> discard (rename-to-trash) -> re-materialize; optional periodic\n  integrity re-verify (re-derive tree git-ids vs the directory name).\n\n## Scope\n\n- In: the SHA-keyed cache, single-flight, the janitor (trigger/policy/mechanism/interlock),\n  startup sweep, self-heal.\n- Out: materialization itself (S1); verdict memoization (deferred fast-follow).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Two concurrent gates requesting the same SHA trigger exactly one materialization\n      (single-flight); the second reads the shared entry.\n- [ ] Evicting an entry while a reader holds it open does not disrupt the in-flight read\n      (delete-on-last-close); new lookups cleanly miss and re-materialize.\n- [ ] The janitor reclaims under a free-space watermark using LRU by touch-on-read mtime\n      (NOT atime), skipping entries within the grace window; runs off the hot path.\n- [ ] Eviction is rename-to-trash then rmtree; no in-place recursive delete of a live entry.\n- [ ] A second process cannot run a GC pass concurrently (exclusive `gc/lock`); population\n      remains lock-free.\n- [ ] No PID/heartbeat lease is used; liveness decisions rest on fds/flock, not PID liveness.\n- [ ] A corrupt/truncated entry is detected on read-error and self-healed by re-materialization.","id":"70c7-8745-2be8-4e5c","parent_id":"1f19-adf2-ffb2-4b09","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"story","title":"Content-addressed snapshot cache + background janitor"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1782519378111574001,"uuid":"a1202c46-5af3-4b0b-a2d0-bc7a425cb9ac"}